text:
🔊پشت زنان ایرانیِ موفق هیچ مردی دیده نشده بجز در..... با دیدن این کلیپ #زنان_دیده_نشده متوجه شدم اگر یک نفر مدافعِ حقوق زنان در کل تاریخ ایران باشه، اون شخص  رضا شاه بزرگ بود، آزادی رضاشاهی باعث خارج کردن زنان و دختران از پستو و ورودشان به دانشگاه، اجتماع و کار بود. فمنیست های واقعی آزادی رضاشاهی بهشون بیشتر چسبید و ترجیح دادند به تو سری خوریِ آخوندی. بانوان حق طلبِ #ایران هر یک همانند صد مرد از حیثیت ایرانی دفاع میکنند، میجنگند تا افتخار می آفرینند. بانوان ایران را تنها نگذارید اینان مادران عزیز ایرانند و مام وطن و سمبل مقاومت ایرانی در برابر اهریمن اسلامی و آخوندی هستند. #صدایشان_را_بشنوید
#m_fروناک 
#metoo #girl  #wearesilent #bringbackourgirls #کرامت_انسانی #رو_به_میهن_پشت_به_دشمن #زنان_ایران #براندازم #مادر_ایران_نوین #شهبانو_فرح_پهلوی #iranregimechange #ایران_را_پس_میگیریم #فرقه_تبهکار  #من_رباط_نیستم  #خزر_قربانی_بقای_رژيم  #رضاشاه_روحت_شاد  #محمد_رضا_شاه_پهلوی  #پرچم_سه_رنگ_شیر_و_خورشید  #rezapahlavi #با_پهلوی_تا_رفراندوم  #شاهزاده_رضا_پهلوی  #مرگ_بر_خامنه_ای #مرگ_بر_آخوند #مرگ_بر_جمهوري_تروريستي_اسلامي

text:
today(19-11-2018) itm business school warangal celebrating international men's day..
most people don't even know that there is, in fact, an internationally recognized day for men... and most people laugh at the idea of celebrating it. "isn't every day men's day?" is the common refrain.
we think that men should be acknowledged, recognized and celebrated... not just for their achievements and conquests, but for the roles they play in our society.
especially in light of the wave of #metoo allegations, and the spotlight that's been aimed at male behaviour, we must take the time to acknowledge that there are men who have been raised well, who treat everyone as equals and make us proud through how they live their lives.

#happymensday
#itmwarangal.

die rezension von hanna weichselbaum findest du unter www.das-buendnis.at/magazin

by the way: heute am 19. november liest hanna herbst um 19:00 im grazer theater am lend aus ihrem buch. die nächste lesung findet am 8. dezember in der arena21 (museumsquartier, wien) um 12:30 statt.

text:
this is not consent.
this is not ok. i am sick to death and beyond disgusted at victim blaming.
"but what were you wearing?"
"how much had you had to drink?"
"were you leading him on?"
"it was probably your fault"
"you got yourself into that situation"
no. no means no. it shouldn't matter what clothing is on your body, how much alcohol is in your system, or the company that you keep. if you say no to sexual activity, it means no.
a 27 year old male has just been found not guilty of raping a 17 year old girl. a few quotes from the trial included, 'we felt attracted to one another on the night.' 'she was not crying at any stage.' and brought up in defence of the accused 'does the evidence out-rule the possibility that she was attracted to the defendant and was open to meeting someone and being with someone? you have to look at the way she was dressed. she was wearing a thong with a lace front.' the thing that makes the last quote even worse is the fact the lawyer defending the accused is a woman! 
then you look at the fact the jury on this particular case was made up of 8 men, and somewhat worse, 4 women! i am appalled that this young 17 year old girl who had the the bravery and strength to stand up in court and profusely state that she did not give this 27 year old man the consent to take her virginity by force has been blamed for what happened to her and made out to be a liar by people who were not and may have never been in her situation. and if they have, then shame on them. 
something needs to be done. 
it is my body to give. it is not yours to take.
#thisisnotconsent #stopvictimblaming #metoo #equality #nomeansno #mybodymychoice #mybodymyrights #womensupportwomen #womenhelpingwomen #istandwithher #ibelieveher

text:
was ist die antwort auf die frage, wer bist du wenn du dich nicht mit deinem beruf oder deiner schulbildung vorstellst, also kein "hi, ich bin katja und ich bin recruiterin und habe politikwissenschaft studiert." was können wir über uns erzählen, wenn es um uns als person geht. 
darüber denke ich, seit ein paar tagen nach. was macht uns aus? was haben wir erlebt?
also eine antwort könnte wohl lauten: hi, ich bin katja, ich bin mit mama, papa und einem bruder aufgewachsen. mein bruder hatte eine behinderung und hat somit eine ganze menge aufmerksamkeit und behandlung gebraucht. ich bin eine große schwester und wohl auch seine beste fürsorge und verteidigung. ich wurde in eine arbeiterfamilie geboren, und so ist eines der zentralen dinge, das ich lernte das man hart arbeiten muss um es gut zu haben. 
außerdem musste man sich in meiner familie zuneigung häufig verdienen, wer sich "daneben" benahm, mit dem wurde nicht mehr geredet, der musste in sein zimmer oder alleine in der küche essen. somit war zuneigung für mich immer damit verknüpft heraus zu finden, welche erwartungen ich erfüllen musste. was wird von mir erwartet, wie kann ich es erfüllen und was übersehe ich. weshalb könnte man auf mich böse sein. eine echt anstrengende art und weise sein leben zu bestreiten. dann gab es ein anderes einschneidendes ereignis in meinem leben. scham, schuld und angst wurden meine ständigen begleiter. ich war 10 jahre alt, ein schüchternes mädchen mit einer altrosa jacke und einem blonden  bobschnitt. er war ein schmieriger typ über 40 mit längeren schwarzen welligen haaren. er fuhr cabrio und wenn er zu besuch kam, hatte er immer geschenke für mich dabei, ich durfte auf seinem schoß sitzen und bei jeder gelegenheit spielte er mit mir oder knuddelte mich. meistens bekam ich von ihm cds, ich liebte musik und durfte mir immer etwas von ihm wünschen. er schenkte mir sehr viel aufmerksamkeit, er hörte mir zu und beschenkte mich. bis zu einem tag an dem ich zu ihm gehen sollte, er war mein babysitter und meine eltern unterwegs. ich erinnere mich noch genau, wie die rollos in seiner wohnung überall nur schlitze hatten, die sonne schien herein und der staub tanzte in der luft.

text_retweet:
no seu concurso vai cair redação?
você não pode ficar sem assinar o jg.

#repost @gabaritandoredacao (@get_repost)
・・・
temas de redação!
por orlando stiebler. "a oxford apontou um aumento de 45% no número de vezes que os usuários pesquisaram a palavra no ano de 2018 e relata que depois de “química”, a palavra que frequentemente a acompanha é “masculinidade”. o termo masculinidade tóxica se refere à epidemia de direitos masculinos, alienação e violência que deram origem ao movimento #metoo cuja a luta é contra o assédio e agressão sexual."
-
fonte: revista galileu.
-
-
além desse significado a palavra toxic (em inglês) escolhida ontem tem outros significados como no caso de uma relação amororosa, nas nossas relações em redes sociais, no ambiente de trabalho, etc.

a escolha do dicionário oxford é extremamente importante, pois muitas vezes pauta debates ao longo do ano, lembro que em 2016 foi pós-verdade (post-truth) e em 2017 youthquake.
-
você já teve uma relação tóxica??? mais sobre o assunto no #jornalgabaritando dessa semana, assine no site @gabaritandoredacao.
-
-

text:
✊✊🏻✊🏼✊🏽✊🏾✊🏿 un an après #metoo, beaucoup reste à faire. le voile s’est enfin levé sur les violences faites aux femmes mais la situation des victimes n’a pas beaucoup changé. au travail, c’est toujours la loi du silence.
salarié·e·s en responsabilité, nous sommes doublement concerné·e·s. nous pouvons être victimes de sexisme et de violences. mais lorsque nous encadrons des équipes, nous avons aussi la responsabilité de contribuer à un environnement de travail non violent, de protéger les victimes et de sanctionner les agresseurs. ceci ne s’improvise pas. c’est la raison pour laquelle il est nécessaire de mettre en place un cadre clair sur les violences sexistes et sexuelles. pour ce faire, la cgt demande l’ouverture de négociations dans toutes les entreprises. (lire la suite du tract dans la tractotheque sur syndicoop.fr)
samedi 24 novembre, marchons pour en finir avec les violences sexistes et sexuelles. ✊✊🏻✊🏼✊🏽✊🏾✊🏿
pour connaître les lieux et horaires des rassemblements : noustoutes.org

text: i found this book fascinating as something to come out of the #metoo movement and the period where abusers of power from the past few years are finally being held accountable for their actions. putney by sofka zinovieff tells a really important story about the abuse in the grey sense instead of the black and white. the strong lolita vibes i mentioned when i started putney were valid by the end, but this is a much more realistic version of that story, with it’s strong sense of justice and realisation and confusion. we’re left with the layers of betrayal that come from abuse and the ripple effect of those layers over years. from toxic friendships to toxic parenting, to repression and warped love, this book kind of had it all with finely calved, unreliable and very believable characters. thank you also to @florenceandthebookparty and @gitana.eleni for inviting me into your discussion, i loved hearing what everyone thought! ♥️ #reading

text:
#internationalmensday 
ahh.. finally the day is here. those stereotypical days we all celebrate to pamper each other, be it #valentinesday or #womensday, no offence i truly enjoy all of them. and why not!? one more reason to be happy. but men usually get lesser credits than they actually deserve. with every #metoo and #feminist posts we tend to forget the men who truly believe in women and stand along side us by being the pillars of strength, courage and love. 
one such amazing man in my life is @thebeardedmirage. recently, i was diagnosed with an ovarian tumor which had almost all the signs of ovarian cancer (luckily it was not cancerous). trust me,  i have never fallen too sick or had bad fever when i was in india and all of a sudden i was bombarded with hospital appointments, blood works and extreme emotions. i was told that there could be a possibility that i might have to loose both ovaries and won't be able to bear a child. these informations were extremely loaded to process, especially without my family around me, but this man was there for me, at every step of the way. 
he was there for me till i cried my lungs out at 4am ist, he asked me to wipe my tears, he reminded me how strong i am, he reminded me that his love was beyond any superficial standards of beauty and societal norms,and everyday he woke me up with a positive attitude and hope which made me even stronger to handle things on my own and unlock my true potentials. luckily my surgery went well and i am recovering pretty well. 
long distance relationship is the hardest on its own but when you have a difficult phase in your life your relationship is put to test and its true potential will be revealed. yes, i am strong but with @thebeardedmirage on my side i am #unbeatable! thanks for being my strength, my confidence, my motivation and my love💋. i couldn't have gone through all this without you being a phone call away. i have and will love and respect you forever but now i know that someday our future kid will too for being a true man😉
happy international men's day, babe!

p.s:@mittai1212 @zin_sowmya @zeelchan_ you girls are my everything. thanks for being my daily dose of happiness 💙

text:
i can't live on like this. i want and have to change something. 
i completely changed myself this year. i lost more weight than i thought i would ever lose, i got a new shorter haircut, i just look completely different now.
the only think i didn't change is my mind. my mind is still as fucked up as it was last year. when i look in the mirror i still think i'm as fat as ever despite losing so much weight. i still think i'm ugly. i still think no one will ever truly love me. i still think everyone is talking shit about me behind my back. 
i'm tired of my mental illness. i'm tired of all this negativity. i told you my story, my fears, just everything you need to know about me.
this is the next chapter. it's time for change. this is my way to recovery, to a happier life less controlled by my mental illness.
.
.

the only think i didn't change is my mind. my mind is still as fucked up as it was last year. when i look in the mirror i still think i am as fat as ever despite losing so much weight. i still think i am ugly. i still think no one will ever truly love me. i still think everyone is talking shit about me behind my back. 
i am tired of my mental illness. i am tired of all this negativity. i told you my story, my fears, just everything you need to know about me.
this is the next chapter. it is time for change. this is my way to recovery, to a happier life less controlled by my mental illness.
.
.

text_retweet:
heute ist der internationale männertag 2018 und ich möchte gerne eine seit #metoo oft gestellte frage beantworten.
was dürfen männer überhaupt noch???
liebe männer*,
ihr dürft darauf scheißen, was für ansprüche an "männlich sein" gestellt werden. ihr dürft (außer grenzen anderer menschen verletzen) alles, was euch glücklich macht. das gilt für jeden menschen, denn wir alle haben ein recht auf persönliche selbstverwirklichung.
ihr dürft gefühle erkennen und zulassen, euren menschenverstand benutzen, privilegien bewusst wahrnehmen und kritisch hinterfragen, humorvoll sein und ungerechtigkeiten ernst nehmen. sowohl frauen*, als auch männer* schön finden und respektvoll sein. mutig, ängstlich, laut, leise, stark und schwach sein, in euch reinhören und anderen zuhören. eure gesundheit ernst nehmen und euch hilfe holen. euch feiern und empören, erfolgreich flirten und ablehnung akzeptieren, lachen und weinen, für euch und für andere einstehen, erklären und fragen, vertrauen und denken, fühlen, hoffen und lieben.
. . .
die fotos habe ich bei @monchi.fromm @chantar @marvynmacnificent und @michibuchinger gemopst. deshalb: *unbezahlte werbung* 😊
. . .

text:
beware of the "temporary fix". .

sometimes when a person tries to leave an abusive relationship, the abuser will ask "what did i do wrong?" or "how can i make things better?"
.
-
the abusive partner will then stop doing the things that upset you (or they'll start doing more of the things that you like), but only for a little while.
.
-
once you trust that he or she is trying to do better, you'll notice the person goes right back to their old ways. that is because the abuser never had any intention to change, the "temporary fix" was only to diffuse the situation just long enough stop you from leaving.
-
.

text:
hej alla nya som hittat hit! 👋🏽 vi är #nowwhat - organisationen som genom tekniska lösningar vill förebygga och stoppa sexuella övergrepp. igår avslutades vårt första riktiga hackathon ever. vi höll hus i norrsken i stockholm, och under en hel helg arbetade femton lag med att ta fram olika tekniska lösningar på hur man ska förebygga och stoppa sexuella övergrepp! vårt hackathon är unikt, för vi bjuder inte enbart tekniskt kompetenta individer, utan också experter inom grundproblematiken kring sexuella övergrepp samt affärsutvecklare/entreprenörer. våra hackathons är alltså interdisciplinära, för vi tror på mångfald, och vi tror att fler perspektiv måste kombineras för att läsa vårt allvarliga samhällsproblem kring #metoo.

vi som arbetat med @nowwhathacks har gjort detta på en ideell basis. #nowwhat är, det vill säga, en ideell organisation som bedrivs av partnerskap, sponsorskap av företag och donationer av individer.

#nowwhat är ett konkret svar på #metoo och vår vision är att erbjuda årliga hackathons tills vi som organisation inte behövs mer! kul att du hittade hit - tillsammans kan vi göra skillnad! 👊🏼💥💛 #norrskenhouse #nowwhathacks #sthlmtech

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
❌ say no to domestic violence ❌
auf den tag genau vor 5 jahren habe ich eine entscheidung getroffen. die entscheidung, mein leben nicht weiterhin in einer ungesunden beziehung zu verbringen. die entscheidung, mein leben selbst zu gestalten, glücklich sein zu wollen.
wenn ich eines gelernt habe dann, dass es nie zu spät ist, um stop zu sagen. ich weiß, es ist nicht leicht, ich weiß, wie viel mut es braucht. und vor allem die richtige unterstützung. damals dachte ich, dass es eben mein schicksal ist, in dieser beziehung leben zu müssen. nun weiß ich, dass ich besseres verdient habe. vor allem respekt und wahre, bedingungslose liebe.
als pazifistin ist gewalt für mich nie in ordnung. und männer, die meinen ihr ego darüber definieren zu müssen wie schlecht sie eine frau behandeln, haben nur meine verachtung verdient. (natürlich auch umgekehrt, aber ich spreche hier aus meiner situation.) deshalb. was mir an diesem tag heut wichtig ist: solltet ihr bemerken, dass jemand schlecht behandelt wird, zeigt zivilcourage und handelt. bringt euch nicht selbst in gefahr, aber gebt der person zu verstehen, dass ihr da seid, dass ihr bereit seid, zu helfen. im akuten fall, ruft die polizei. 
aus meiner sicht kann ich sagen, ich hätte mich gefreut, wenn jemand für mich eingetreten wäre. wenn mir einmal jemand gezeigt hätte - ich helfe dir da raus. 
nicht immer wird diese hilfe auch angenommen - denn "er will sich ja ändern" oder vielmehr aus reiner angst, was bei einer trennung passieren könnte- aber versucht es. bitte. es gibt tolle einrichtungen, die helfen können! keine frau (und natürlich auch kein mann) sollte in so einer beziehung leben müssen.
#saynotodomesticviolence #gegenhäuslichegewalt #stoptheviolence #gewaltgegenfrauen #metoo

text:
a little about my story 🌸. i grew up with not alot of money, didnt have a proper father figure in my life and my mother worked to support herself and 3 kids. this ment unfortunately i faced alot of neglect she worked alot ,my dad and i didnt have the best bond and my older brothers didn't want much to do with me. i struggled in school because i couldnt focus , i wouldnt bring home friends because i was embarrassed of where i lived..
.
fast forward abit i went through a trauma that has impacted the rest of my life . it has tainted every part of my being and led me to self-harm and eating disorders when i was a young teen. back then i was thin however i never sore it i struggled with constant hate towards myself and putting myself in unsafe situations because i craved affection due to neglect. this followed into my adult life being with a partner who emotionally neglected me and i began hating my body again . 2 years ago i became free and started a journey to love myself i've faught very hard and i will always be fighting . i've been burned by many people ive loved friends who claim they are but turn out to be fake , i could go into alot more depth about alot of this but i guess i'm not saying this because i want people to feel sorry for me but because i dont often tell myself how strong i am and how bloody far i've come !! to be able to wear something like this and actually feel confident after awhile is such a massive step for me and i am proud of myself. but i wouldn't be here if it wasnt for my peoples so i thank them because they are what keeps this girl up ❤❤.

fast forward abit i went through a trauma that has impacted the rest of my life . it has tainted every part of my being and led me to self-harm and eating disorders when i was a young teen. back then i was thin however i never sore it i struggled with constant hate towards myself and putting myself in unsafe situations because i craved affection due to neglect. this followed into my adult life being with a partner who emotionally neglected me and i began hating my body again . 2 years ago i became free and started a journey to love myself i have faught very hard and i will always be fighting . i have been burned by many people ive loved friends who claim they are but turn out to be fake , i could go into alot more depth about alot of this but i guess i am not saying this because i want people to feel sorry for me but because i do not often tell myself how strong i am and how bloody far i have come !! to be able to wear something like this and actually feel confident after awhile is such a massive step for me and i am proud of myself. but i would not be here if it wasnt for my peoples so i thank them because they are what keeps this girl up ❤❤.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
happy @international_mens_day to all the amazing sons, brothers, fathers, uncles, granddads and husbands out there...
.
.
the men who hustle hard to provide for their families...
.
.
the men who take on the dirty, unpleasant, or high-risk jobs...
.
.
the men who have to spend time away from their loved ones to serve their countries or provide humanitarian relief...
.
.
the men who are fighting not to become a statistic, and who reach out for help even when they're scared of being seen as weak...
.
.
the men who've been wrongly alienated from their precious kids, or falsely accused of crimes they didn't commit...
.
.
the men battling addictions and trauma, who fight every day to be a better person, even when society tells them 'a leopard never changes its spots'... .
.
i see you. i believe in you. you are appreciated & this world needs you.
.
.
special shout out to some of the amazing men i know below: 
my hubby chris, glen hulley (founder of anti-child exploitation organisation @project.karma )... my mate @tim_alexander_official who helps so many people (including many women) to regain their strength, confidence, and learn to defend themselves... my fellow mental health warriors @danpricey85 , matt runnalls, and patrick lawson (3words, mental health awareness) who are forever hustling to stop men from going down the road that once almost took their lives...
.
.
and of course, the ever-humble, inspiring, and world-changing individual that is @kevinhinesstory (one of my heroes).

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

there are currently 3 billion social media users worldwide. 1 billion from instagram. this means that over a third of the world’s population is using some form of social media to communicate, making social media marketing an imperative tactic for boosting leads.
so here is how it has changed the way we communicate.
1. it has created a sense of urgency and a need to share. 
now we have a need to share something with our audience. 
our audience have become our besties because why tell one person at a time when you can multiple people at once.
2. it has revolutionized word of mouth marketing;  before we had to tell someone to tell anyone but now, when a client feels good, they can post it up and help increase sales.
3. it has provided a perspective on faraway places; with the era of live streaming, the world is in our huts. now someone in faraway america can recognize girls in borno state. we can start our challenge, stop a movement by just saying #metoo 
4. we can now share our stories ourselves instead of just highlights. we can now revolutionize the way we think because i can be in nigeria but i am serving the world.
5. it has made messages so personal; now we can tell stories and make the dm personal. we can ensure that we grow relationships and find ways to be more personable.
6. it brought news back to the millennials; lots of people don’t like the news but when we have pages like instablog giving news in a creative way, we stay glued.
now you know all this, how do you plan to ensure you use it to get ready for 2019?

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

with ficial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

tweet_full:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
documenting your thoughts with a pen and paper (or computer) is a way to acknowledge past experiences that may be causing you pain and reintegrating them into your life so they become a part of you. it helps bring order to your deepest thoughts and fears and enables you to learn from the person who knows you best: you.

journaling provides a safe environment that enables you to face your traumas. when that happens, remarkable healing follows. indeed, studies find that journaling can reduce pain, improve depression, and even lower markers of inflammation. #youwillbearwitness #emdr #erinfado #ptsdawareness #ptsd #stopracism #stopbullying #stopchildabuse #peterfox #ptsdsurvivor #ptsdrecovery #trauma #metoo #therapydog #cardinalpell #dissociativeidentitydisorder

text:
hallo und guten morgen... 🌄🌄🌄 na wie verläuft denn euer start in die neue woche? mein wochenstart verläuft wieder mal ruhig.. ich geniesse einen freien morgen und dafür stapeln sich heute nachmittag die termine 🙄 und ab dezember ist eh alles anders.. da startet meine arbeitswoche auch montags vor 5. das heisst der wecker ⏰ reisst mich dann aus den träumen. 🙈 ne.. quatsch.. meistens bin ich ja eh vor dem lauten teil munter.. 😁 bin ja gespannt wie ich das ganze in sachen mealprep und so hin kriege... weil am wochenende liegt mein fokus definitiv nicht bei dem gedanken: was nehm ich auf arbeit mit. 🙄 wochenende ist eben wochenende. 
gestern abend nach der wanderung gab es nur eines.. eine runde 🏊‍♀️ in der wanne 🛁 und dann musste was einfaches.. warmes... und sätigendes auf den tisch.. schreit nach #suppe, findet ihr nicht auch? die zutaten findet ihr eigentlich auf dem bild.. außer zwiebel, knoblauch und gewürze.. bis später.. dann mal... #abnehmenohnezuhungern #changeyourbody #cleaneating #healtyfood #instafood #ranandenspeck #ichliebemeinneuesleben  #teamzuckerfrei#weilesummichgeht  #abgerechnetwirdamstrand #zuckerfrei #weizenfrei #cleanfood #intervallfasten #16:18 #kochenmachtspass #herbst

text:
"i was raised to put others' needs first. the older i get, the more courage i feel to destroy that culturally accepted pattern.  i'm driven to model righteous living for my daughter as the  #metoo backlash tries to keep women following rules - be quiet, pretty, behave.  i'm curious and excited to see what happens the more i listen to my inner voice and honour my dreams. in my mind, there are no limits now." - mel
.
- mother, playwright, woman warrior. in 2017, melanie's midlife crisis crashed headlong into the #metoo movement. the result was midlife clarity and a one woman show: "shield maiden." follow her on facebook at shield maiden play and shieldmaidenplay.com
.
to see the evolving collection of amazing ajummas, go to the #100ajummas project site. link in bio
.

tweet_full:
"i was raised to put others' needs first. the older i get, the more courage i feel to destroy that culturally accepted pattern.  i am driven to model righteous living for my daughter as the  #metoo backlash tries to keep women following rules - be quiet, pretty, behave.  i am curious and excited to see what happens the more i listen to my inner voice and honour my dreams. in my mind, there are no limits now." - mel
.
- mother, playwright, woman warrior. in 2017, melanie's midlife crisis crashed headlong into the #metoo movement. the result was midlife clarity and a one woman show: "shield maiden." follow her on facebook at shield maiden play and shieldmaidenplay.com

text:
• taking back l.a. • the beauty of it all is that it was never gone. i may have temporarily left a piece of myself there, but i got her back.  i got her back on my own terms and turned over a new leaf long awaiting.  i also happened to connect and work with some of the most talented, passionate and kind humans i’ve ever known.  i’m in love with life.  not that lusty sort of rush, but that grounded sense of just knowing and being.  never say never.  stay open, work hard, and find compassion for yourself and others.  it’s been almost a decade in the making.  we find our own freedom when the timing is right.  if it doesn’t work the first time.  try again. keep trying.  the possibilities are endless. if i’m speaking somewhat cryptically, i’m open to questions. 🤷🏻‍♀️ .
.
.
those of you who know, you know and i love you.  i’ve learned a lot about people. i appreciate those who let me in and allow me to let them in.  thank you for being there through the process. the fun part is that we get to celebrate the victories together.  i might just tag some of you for being a part of this journey no matter where we are now in life. ♥️ #losangeles #freedom #perspective

text:
babak baru perlawanan terhadap kekerasan seksual telah datang. suara korban tak bisa lagi disangkal. mendesak peradilan yang berpihak dan menuntut setiap tempat jadi ruang aman dan menghargai perempuan. .
.
namun begitu sikap para pengambil kebijakan belum sesuai harapan. korban balik disudutkan, diminta untuk mengurangi kebebasan, dan malah diancam pidana dan dikriminalisasikan. .
.
teman-teman semua, ayo datang dan ramaikan seminar sehari #akhirisekarang kekerasan seksual dan diskriminasi gender dalam dunia kerja. bersama dengan beragam organisasi serikat buruh, mari suarakan dan kuatkan perlawanan kita, mewujudkan pabrik, kantor, kampus, lingkungan kita aman dan bebas dari kekerasan seksual. .
.
selasa, 27 november 2018, pukul 09.00 s.d 17.30 di gedung lbh jakarta
.
.

text:
this article focuses on calculating for reparations, looking at the costs of police violence from multiple perspectives. may we all have healing justice and #endpoliceterrorism.

first, there is no one method or formula for determining reparations.

so much of the violence we experience is personalized. the violence we experience as individuals is always shared by other people and communities, yet how it affects us is embodied and related to who we are in this earth walk. that's why this method was designed for people like you and #metoo.

second, calculating reparations is always an economic and spiritual practice.

above all, the spiritual dimension of this method is central, and survivors must lead each initiative. the point is to foster healing, not pay for therapy and legal costs, and give people the support we require to create solutions for ourselves and our beloved communities. so, what does healing mean for you as a survivor of the violence you seek to stop? given your daily life and needs at this time, what do you need to put in place to learn and apply the method?

from a purely economic perspective, what aspects of healing can financial reparations facilitate? this question is the most direct, but it isn't as simple as it sounds. for example, you might desire therapy and know that therapists cost a rate of, say $60-250 an hour in your town. what if no therapist in your local beloved community speaks your mother language of quechua and that's the language in which you sense the world? what is the honest price tag for your therapy sessions if you have to travel three hours to see a therapist who shares your cultural, linguistic, ancestral perspective? 
what else is at play when it comes to money? emotions such as grief and anger, fear and pain, #shame and guilt always bubble to the surface when delving into traumatic experiences, and poverty is its own #trauma. what can make this learning process a means of healing financial trauma in your personal life and that of your #beloved community?

calculating for #reparations is traveling through time and body. it means seeing a #horror happen again and again from multiple perspectives like a #baby in #jail.
name: darshan elena campos

text:
#111 #dothemath #followthemoneytrail 
part of #healing and moving through feelings of #guilt and #shame is finding allies, people who #inspire and remind you of your #beauty and divine #nature. healing is the heart of the many global movements for #reparations and #decolonization.

healing is the polar opposite of what most of the world's political and business leadership seek to sell. hence the title of this article, which speaks to my own sorry experiences over the last four years.

#googleprotectssexualpredators.

if you know me and my work, you know that i write a lot about guilt and shame as currencies. i also talk about using them to fund healing projects such as a #migratinguniversity and #decolonialbusinessacademy. it’s true.

while i’d rather not shame and guilt people and companies into giving monies, we need the cash. i do. just read “$6.42 and the dream” on linkedin. believe me, i don't want to remember the how and why of how google has been protecting one sexual predator that i know by name and many others such as andy rubin, but sometimes we can't forget or move forward without a formal #reckoning and financial reparations.

that's what #metoo and #timesup and #niunamenos and #balancetonporc represent: reckoning and reparations.

sometimes we experience situations where healing can most fully happen when financial and material resources are available. decolonization and reparations are not metaphors. they are economic relationships that promote love, healing, and #resilience. that's why i see guilt and shame as global currencies. may they soon go out of fashion, just like #fastfashion.

i’m looking for $500k to fund a free and open migrating university and decolonial business academy. this school will teach people how to design and elevate businesses that heal us as individuals and diverse peoples who share a global ecosystem in transition. 
the method at the heart of the work is called decolonial bizness world, and you can learn it by watching my videos on 👺youtube, which is one of hundreds of companies that 🤖 google aka 👹 alphabet owns 
#decolonialbiznessworld is made for the magicians of the global economy....

text:
femme wave presents: sex hysteria afterimage [8/10]: an instagram exhibition by @prdct .
.
the root of these issue lies in the fact that the lived experiences of sex workers remains largely underground. the truth of it is hard to swallow, eons away from the damaging narrative that has spread from its roots in the anti-sex trafficking movement:

that sex workers are trashy women
 migrant women
 black women
 and *only* women.
.
that they are disposable
diseased
addicted
and dirty

that they are unskilled
 unintelligent
 undeserving
 and unloved. .
.
the perpetual stereotype of the ‘dirty hooker’ has tarnished conversations of sex workers’ rights and safety. sex workers are not the ‘perfect victim’ that #metoo and political commentary feed off of, living on the frontlines of the violences that afflicts them. much like the afterimage affect used by mccann, the stereotype perpetually overshadows the truth, and the only solution is the conscious decision to continue pulling sex work into the forefront of conversations of sex, intersectionality, and discrimination. 
_________
art [8/10] by @prdct
music by @deepsabrina
essay by @buates.mckenzie

text:
babak baru perlawanan terhadap kekerasan seksual telah datang. suara korban tak bisa lagi disangkal. mendesak peradilan yang berpihak dan menuntut setiap tempat jadi ruang aman dan menghargai perempua. .
.
namun begitu sikap para pengambil kebijakan belum sesuai harapan. korban balik disudutkan, diminta untuk mengurangi kebebasan, dan malah diancam pidana dan dikriminalisasikan. .
.
teman-teman semua, ayo datang dan ramaikan seminar sehari #akhirisekarang kekerasan seksual dan diskriminasi gender dalam dunia kerja. bersama dengan beragam organisasi serikat buruh, mari suarakan dan kuatkan perlawanan kita, mewujudkan pabrik, kantor, kampus, lingkuan kita aman dan bebas kekerasan seksual. .
.
selasa, 27 november 2018, pukul 09.00 s.d 17.30 di gedung lbh jakarta
.
.

.

text: for the last nevertheless shoot of the year we were so fortunate to sit down with amaani lyle who was a writer’s assistant on friends back in 1999 - total dream job. but what amaani experienced in the writer’s room on this incredibly popular show was egregiously inappropriate language about women constantly which fostered a hostile work environment for her that she, like so many of us believe is just the price we have to pay as women in the workplace. it was fascinating to hear about a case that might have turned out differently if it happened today. no matter the outcome, i admire amaani’s courage to use her voice and stand up for other storytellers that would later fill her shoes. #nevertheless #metoo #timesup

text:
has someone invaded your personal space? whatever is not comfortable is not acceptable. #metooindia
the trauma of an invasion of personal space, physical touch, emotional abuse or gestures may be immediate, long term or relived trauma.  the trauma of the act has its own consequences.  it may also be dependent on how you were made to feel apart from the act, were you fired from the job or otherwise coerced, were others aware of it and how did they react to it, how much work pressure was put on you. it is also linked to whether you were listened to or believed.let us help someone who comes to us with a case of assault, we should try to help them. it will lessen the chances of long term effects of the trauma
the #metooindia movement is affecting the mental health of many. those coming out with their stories, those not coming out with their stories, those tasked with letting the stories been known to the public and anyone who has been in a similar situation before. we're doing a series on #metoo and #mentalhealth so that we can teach you how to help yourself.

#repost @belinda_vegan
・・・
all use of animals for food, clothing, entertainment, pets or experimentation involves utilising animals against their will, and - in the vast majority of cases - involves their suffering and deaths. we are brought up to believe in our current society that we need to consume or make use of other animals but this is neither ethical nor necessary. instead, vegans choose to live a lifestyle that respects other animals as sentient individuals whose lives have meaning and do not consume, wear or use animal products or take part in activities which exploit animals. today, being vegan is easy, proven to be healthy and needn't cost more. 
_
being vegan is about living a lifestyle that does not cause suffering, harm or death to animals, and allowing animals to be free to choose the way they want to live. other animals are sentient beings like us, with their own needs, desires and interests. we now know that like us, they can experience a wide range of sensations and emotions such as happiness, pain, pleasure, fear, hunger, sadness, boredom, frustration or contentment. they are aware of the world and what happens to them matters to them. their lives have intrinsic value - they are not inferior beings nor just here as resources or tools for human use. discriminating against non-human animals or believing them to be inferior solely because they belong to a different species is known as speciesism and is as unscientific and unjust as racism or sexism. 
_
embrace veganism🌱

being vegan is about living a lifestyle that does not cause suffering, harm or death to animals, and allowing animals to be free to choose the way they want to live. other animals are sentient beings like us, with their own needs, desires and interests. we now know that like us, they can experience a wide range of sensations and emotions such as happiness, pain, pleasure, fear, hunger, sadness, boredom, frustration or contentment. they are aware of the world and what happens to them matters to them. their lives have intrinsic value - they are not inferior beings nor just here as resources or tools for human use. discriminating against non-human animals or believing them to be inferior solely because they belong to a different species is known as speciesism and is as unscientific and unjust as racism or sexism. 
_

text:
thunder 
lightning 
but mostly rain,
live within your eyes. 
dampening the shore of your cheeks with barely concealed emotion. 
the storm batters against your broken soul, scattering the pieces on the roaring winds. 
your body in a constant tempest-tossed state. 
yet the beauty found within your pain,
the strength in the trials you have overcome, 
the wisdom in each broken piece of you, 
lies within your ocean eyes. .
.
.

text:
good news is, as a mother to young boy and girl, i can safely say that the new generation of boys who will be men tomorrow, are ready for an equal world. they walk side by side with strong girls in school and only know the idea of an equal world of opportunities for everyone. when i look at them, i get a sense of hope amidst all this chaos that has just overtaken us.  it was perfect timing for the storm to start, for after the dust settles and a cool downpour follows, what will emerge is a cleaner and clearer tomorrow for everyone. the only people who will suffer or be left behind will be the ones who do not embrace this change. the feminine rising is not just demanding their rights but in turn an equal world for our future generation.

text:
what needs to be done to maintain healthy teeth: *limit sweet foods *limit sweet drinks
*try to have healthy snacks such as fresh fruit, vegetable sticks, natural yogurt, plain popcorn, soups or cheese.
*choose fresh fruit over dried fruit
*cut down the sugar added to cups of tea and coffee.
*drink fluoridated tap water and plain milk instead of soft drinks, juice or cordial.
*have a piece of cheese after consuming sweet or acidic food as dairy products assist in reversing the decay process.

anniversary gig: artist 2 - priyal @youarenow is spoken word artist, who identifies herself as a multiverse gypsy clown. she explores and interprets anthropological storytelling through writing, visual arts and handicrafts. she has performed poetry in vietnam, cambodia, egypt, nepal, uganda and india. her poetry is a provocative vomit of existential truths; exploring the nature of identity, gender, violence, sexuality, dissent, love and freedom. wildly queer, her poetry is futility’s purpose and equality’s dream. at our gig she let it out and spoke about #metoo movement. it was a powerful, provocative set which definitely packed a punch. having seen priyal @youarenow perform at sofar sounds goa in the beginning of the year, we must say she has taken her game to the next level. pc: @the_photo_healer @sofarsounds  @roarwithsimba @strangerandsons #sofar #sofarsounds #spokenword #artist  #poetry #spokenwordpoetry #spokenwordartist #freetheverse #artistsofinstagram #artistsoninstagram #storytelling #art #provocative #metoo  #anniversary

text:
a mini skirt. a t-shirt. sweatpants. jeans. these are the kinds of clothes rape victims wear. because rapists don’t discriminate between people who are dressed “provocatively” and those who are “just dressed.” although people are far more aware than ever before of the pervasiveness of sexual assault and power dynamics, the myth that clothing can be used as justification for sexual violence is as prevalent as ever. every day, rape victims who confide in friends, family or even lawyers are asked four words: “what were you wearing?” this not only detracts from the feelings or details of the victim’s experience, but it also forces victims to ask themselves, “is this my fault?” the concept that women should avoid dressing “like sluts” in order not to be victimized is nothing new. by rationalizing that victims are somehow deserving of their circumstances, we are telling the perpatrators and rapists that they aren’t at fault for the crimes they have committed. 
when it comes to sex crimes, clothing just doesn’t matter. and, not only does this misconception contribute to the belief that a victim is at fault for his or her sexual assault, but it also removes a feeling of safety for victims to come forward about what has happened to them for fear of being judged, blamed and even persecuted. with that shame, fewer victims report sexual assaults and suffer alone, which leads to fewer rapists being brought to justice and more instances of rapists repeating their crimes to either the same victims or new ones. all this blaming and questioning of victims simply feeds #rapeculture, a sociological concept used to describe a setting in which rape is normalized due to attitudes about gender and sexuality. 
society needs to recognize that the only question to ask a victim of #sexualassault is “what can i do to help?” asking a victim what he or she wore when they were attacked is irrelevant, damaging and ignorant. removing blame and shame from the dialogue will empower victims to report their attacks and begin their recovery.
#sexyaftersexualassault #thisisnotconsent #nomorevictimblaming #endrapeculture #metoo #mentoo #bystanderintervention #consent #feminism #nomeansno #timesup

text:
i gave up on vs a long time ago because of their horrifically offensive marketing.
・・・
"dear victoria’s secret,

i was appalled when i saw the demeaning comments about women your chief marketing officer, ed razek, made to vogue last week. as hard as it is to believe, he said the following: “we attempted to do a television special for plus-sizes [in 2000]. no one had any interest in it, still don’t.” “it’s like, why doesn’t your show do this? shouldn’t you have transsexuals in the show? no. no, i don’t think we should. well, why not? because the show is a fantasy.” i’ve read and re-read the interview at least 20 times, and each time i read it i’m even angrier. how in 2018 can the cmo of any public company — let alone one that claims to be for women — make such shocking, derogatory statements? you market to men and sell a male fantasy to women. but at thirdlove, we think beyond, as you said, a “42-minute entertainment special.” your show may be a “fantasy” but we live in reality. our reality is that women wear bras in real life as they go to work, breastfeed their children, play sports, care for ailing parents, and serve their country. haven’t we moved beyond outdated ideas of femininity and gender roles? it’s time to stop telling women what makes them sexy — let us decide. we’re done with pretending certain sizes don’t exist or aren’t important enough to serve. and please stop insisting that inclusivity is a trend. i founded thirdlove five years ago because it was time to create a better option. thirdlove is the antithesis of victoria’s secret. we believe the future is building a brand for every woman, regardless of her shape, size, age, ethnicity, gender identity, or sexual orientation. this shouldn’t be seen as groundbreaking, it should be the norm. 
let’s listen to women. let’s respect their intelligence. let’s exceed their expectations. let women define themselves. as you said ed, “we’re nobody’s thirdlove, we’re their first love.” we are flattered for the mention, but let me be clear: we may not have been a woman’s first love but we will be her last. to all women everywhere, we see you, and we hear you. your reality is enough. to each her own." #metoo

i was appalled when i saw the demeaning comments about women your chief marketing officer, ed razek, made to vogue last week. as hard as it is to believe, he said the following: “we attempted to do a television special for plus-sizes [in 2000]. no one had any interest in it, still don’t.” “it’s like, why doesn’t your show do this? shouldn’t you have transsexuals in the show? no. no, i don’t think we should. well, why not? because the show is a fantasy.” i’ve read and re-read the interview at least 20 times, and each time i read it i’m even angrier. how in 2018 can the cmo of any public company — let alone one that claims to be for women — make such shocking, derogatory statements? you market to men and sell a male fantasy to women. but at thirdlove, we think beyond, as you said, a “42-minute entertainment special.” your show may be a “fantasy” but we live in reality. our reality is that women wear bras in real life as they go to work, breastfeed their children, play sports, care for ailing parents, and serve their country. haven’t we moved beyond outdated ideas of femininity and gender roles? it’s time to stop telling women what makes them sexy — let us decide. we’re done with pretending certain sizes don’t exist or aren’t important enough to serve. and please stop insisting that inclusivity is a trend. i founded thirdlove five years ago because it was time to create a better option. thirdlove is the antithesis of victoria’s secret. we believe the future is building a brand for every woman, regardless of her shape, size, age, ethnicity, gender identity, or sexual orientation. this shouldn’t be seen as groundbreaking, it should be the norm. 
let’s listen to women. let’s respect their intelligence. let’s exceed their expectations. let women define themselves. as you said ed, “we’re nobody’s thirdlove, we’re their first love.” we are flattered for the mention, but let me be clear: we may not have been a woman’s first love but we will be her last. to all women everywhere, we see you, and we hear you. your reality is enough. to each her own." #metoo

text:
давай поговорим?
-о чём?
тем как таковых и нет...действительно -пока
в мою голову часто лезут странные и непонятные мысли...последние два года я устаю натягивать улыбку и лживое счастье...и в этом году было несколько таких случаев когда я просто чувствовала колоссальную отдачу...один из случаев дал мне понять, что я правда нужна как человек и это тот самый друг и комментировать я пожалуй не буду🤯 моё любимое существо разделяется 50/50 потому что я иногда себя чувствую настолько гадко и неприятно...а иногда теплее даже под одеялом не бывает💫
я заглядываю в прошлое и оно меня не тянет назад...я живу в одной комнате с эпицентром моей возможной смерти и антиконтроля...это бред для всех кроме меня и будет бредом...однако такая путаница у меня каждую ночь... #мысливслух#ночь#путаница#life#eyes#time#metoo

text: en irlanda absuelven al violador de una niña de 17 años. el abogado defensor argumentó: «¿la evidencia descarta la posibilidad de que ella se sintiera atraída por el acusado y estuviera dispuesta a conocer a alguien y estar con alguien?», «tienen que mirar cómo iba vestida. llevaba un tanga de encaje». «el problema no es solo el abogado, es el sistema que lo permite», dijo mary crilly, directora del centro de violencia sexual de cork y una de las impulsoras de las protestas. «lo que viste una mujer es asunto suyo, y no implica interés ni consentimiento. nunca es su culpa». #thisisnotconsent #thisisnotconsent #thisisnotconsent #estonoesconsentimiento #estonoesconsentimiento #ibelieveher #ibeliveher #yolecreo #amigayotecreo #noesno #noesno #yotecreo #niunamenos #metoo #metoo

text:
weekend update: • michael avenatti, famous attorney for adult film actress stormy daniels when she came out against president trump, was accused of domestic violence towards his wife. the irony involved is that avenatti has grown to become a figurehead for the #metoo campaign, a movement that proclaims that all women should be heard and believed when they claim they have been assaulted.....................................
the wildfires still rage on in northern and southern california, causing a confirmed death toll of almost 80 people, with over a thousand still missing.............................................cnn sued president trump this week after trump denied jim acosta access to the white house, saying he was not behaving and that a reporter in the white house needs to “act with respect”. the court decided late this week that acosta’s white house press pass needed to be restored as it’s restraint was a violation of the first amendment.

text:
i am still so incredibly moved and inspired by my conversation with the beautiful force advocate and organizer @taranajaneen. 
tarana is the activist and organizer who began the #metoo movement in 2006, a watershed movement that's now spotlighted internationally, but not without the help and drive of its fearless leader. i am humbled to sit in her presence and engage in a conversation about her experience and insights on how we can build stronger, safer, more inclusive communities. 
i, like many others, first learned about tarana and her impactful work when the #metoo movement ignited hollywood, fashion and the cultural industries. i was immediately struck by the depth of her story and her work, and we finally had the opportunity to meet in person when she graciously attended our fall 2018 runway show in february. her spirit and strength feels contagious, inspiring and encouraging those around her to look inside themselves and take action.
tarana, you are radiant with sharp substance, soul, levity and honesty. we are living in a day and age that demands action, conversation and education, and i am so grateful to you for being the empowered heroine that you are. 
everyone, please, listen to our conversation with tarana on our igtv. we are living in a dangerous time and our best solution is to engage in an dialogue. listen to her, sit with her words, and let them empower you the way they did me. xpg
📸 @kylarae_ 
#pgworld #pgmuse #strongerincolour #femininitywithabite #beautywithsubstance #luxurywithsoul

text:
.
tracks i walk you'd trip over.
judge, if you want, go on...
won't change my chapters.
where were you that night...
his hands making filthy?
and during vodka numb days
when a mother forgot a mouth?
where was your discernment 
when blue lights stabbed windows 
and my crib was a screaming witness?
your high and sanctimonious hands
never guided schooldays of shame
when hunger hid under dirty dresses
and too small shoes bit each step
between bus stop bullies and failure
between chemical cures and those
smiling big dollar men telling fortunes
how i could eat, how i could fucking fly
for doing nothing more than simply
all the things already done to me for free.
turn your powdered nose up at me
step by with fat pockets sanctuary nests
as i dance with demons you cannot grasp
and tell yourself you're so much better
tell yourself the lie, you could not be me.
.
.
poem "the lie" by t.stark 
artwork by @jamesearleyartstudio
.
.

text:
“when the whole world is silent, even one voice becomes powerful” - maya angelou 
the #metoo movement has recently become popular, and the voices of women who have been through unbelievable experiences is finally being heard -- only because they are finally speaking up and there are social movements that allow them to do so. i am particularly passionate about this subject and am doing a project on women in the south asian community who have been sexually abused. coming from this culture, i myself am very aware of the silence forced upon women when it comes to matters like this. in order to bring more awareness to this in our community, i am trying to break the taboo nature of this subject. if you are comfortable enough to do so please use your voice by sharing your story with me. i will make sure it is confidential by keeping your name out of it. my main goal is to share with everyone just how serious this problem is, and i hope that together we can all do something to change it. your strength and courage does not go unnoticed. 💪🏽❤️#womenempowerment #useyourvoice #whyididntreport #girlpower #browngirls #womensupportingwomen #sexualassaultsurvivors #sexualassaultvictims #survivors #sexualassault
tweet_full:
“when the whole world is silent, even one voice becomes powerful” - maya angelou 
the #metoo movement has recently become popular, and the voices of women who have been through unbelievable experiences is finally being heard -- only because they are finally speaking up and there are social movements that allow them to do so. i am particularly passionate about this subject and am doing a project on women in the south asian community who have been sexually abused. coming from this culture, i myself am very aware of the silence forced upon women when it comes to matters like this. in order to bring more awareness to this in our community, i am trying to break the taboo nature of this subject. if you are comfortable enough to do so please use your voice by sharing your story with me. i will make sure it is confidential by keeping your name out of it. my main goal is to share with everyone just how serious this problem is, and i hope that together we can all do something to change it. your strength and courage does not go unnoticed. 💪🏽❤️#womenempowerment #useyourvoice #whyididntreport #girlpower #browngirls #womensupportingwomen #sexualassaultsurvivors #sexualassaultvictims #survivors #sexualassault

text:
my spelling hasn’t changed much since i was 10 years old (thank god for my editor) but my relationship with god has. i started out in this world, living in a bubble both literally and figuratively with a very naive and superficial belief that god was “upstairs.” but after years of turning my back on him and going on my own experiential journey through the dark wilderness of pain and suffering, i came back with the realization and understanding that he is not “upstairs” or “out there” but right here, right here inside of me, and has been for every step of my journey. i can’t wait to share my entire story. one that is so much more universal than just a story of sexual assault/abuse.
to quote one of my favorite authors, @mariannewilliamson —my story is a “return to love.” ❤️

text:
i’m afraid to leave 
my house all the time. 
i hate the attention,
i hate the reason for the attention. 
growing up, 
no one wanted to touch me. 
now—-that’s all they want. 
it sounds strange, 
but i thought after 25 
i would stop being desirable. 
there’s a line from 
the office that says that. 
but that’s not happening. 
i get more beautiful everyday. 
if i stay here, i face that. 
if i stay here, i have to. //
“before you walk into church can i just tell you something? just know all these girls you look at, there’s a person in there, ok? that’s just their packaging alright?”
“yes, caroline, i know...”
